objects.name: speccom
objects.description: SpecCom is a malicious 32-bit Windows executable that uses HTTP for command and control. It polls hard-coded URL paths for tasking embedded inside HTML comment tags, with tasking data Base64-encoded and obfuscated via multiple layers of XOR using a hard-coded malware key and a traffic key. Capabilities include executing arbitrary Windows command-prompt commands as new processes and uploading Base64-encoded data to temporary log files that are exfiltrated. It communicates via the Windows wininet API to C2 domains (e.g., infodocs.kginfocom[.]com) using POST requests to /gin/kw.asp (tasking) and /gin/tab.asp (output). The sample described does not install persistence and employs defense evasion such as dynamically built strings, XOR-obfuscated configuration, indirect invocation through a 'Help and Support' window thread, and attempts to disguise suspicious API usage.

objects.name: SpecCom_get_mac_address
objects.description: YARA rule to detect related activity.
objects.pattern:
rule SpecCom_get_mac_address {
    meta:
        author = "NCSC"
        description = "Detects SpecCom obtaining MAC address"

    strings:
        $ = {8D 8D F0 80 FF FF 51 8D 8D FC 80 FF FF 51 C7 85 F0 80 FF FF
90 7E 00 00 FF D0 8B C8 33 C0 C6 45 F4 00 8D 7D F5 AB 66 AB AA 85 C9 0F
85 1D 01 00 00 53 6A 25 5E 6A 30 5A 6A 32 59 8B C6 66 89 45 8C 8B C2 66
89 45 8E 6A 58 8B C1 66 89 45 90}
        $ = {8D 8D 00 81 FF FF 51 8D 95 04 81 FF FF 52 C7 85 00 81 FF FF
90 7E 00 00 FF D0 85 C0 0F 85 C7 00 00 00 8B 85 9C 82 FF FF 8B C8 C1 E9
08 0F B6 D1 52 0F B6 C0 50 8B 85 98 82 FF FF 8B C8 C1 E9 18 51 8B D0 C1
EA 10 0F B6 CA 51 8B D0 C1 EA 08 0F B6 CA 0F B6 D0 51 52 8D 45 94}
    condition:
        (uint16(0) == 0x5A4D and uint16(uint32(0x3c)) == 0x4550) and any
of them
